{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586018","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586018"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:24:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:24:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15049"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15049","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15049"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.54,0.12,0.08,0.12,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7737"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67571"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7737","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7737"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15049"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53023"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"},{"type":"tags","id":"8125"},{"type":"tags","id":"9876"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18893"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18897"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18900"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67571","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67571"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EHepatorenal syndrome is a serious complication of advanced liver disease characterised by progressive kidney dysfunction. It occurs in patients with portal hypertension and ascites.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pathophysiology of hepatorenal syndrome?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Functional renal failure without structural kidney damage","Direct toxic injury to renal tubular cells","Immune complex deposition in glomeruli","Primary renal arterial thrombosis","Acute tubular necrosis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHepatorenal syndrome is characterised by \u003Cstrong\u003Efunctional renal failure without structural kidney damage\u003C/strong\u003E. The pathophysiology involves portal hypertension leading to splanchnic vasodilation, which reduces effective circulating volume. This triggers compensatory mechanisms including activation of the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system, causing intense renal vasoconstriction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect toxic injury to renal tubular cells\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in nephrotoxic acute kidney injury but not hepatorenal syndrome\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmune complex deposition in glomeruli\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of glomerulonephritis but not hepatorenal syndrome\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary renal arterial thrombosis\u003C/strong\u003E would cause structural kidney damage and is not part of the syndrome\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute tubular necrosis\u003C/strong\u003E represents structural damage to the kidneys and is a different pathological process\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key feature distinguishing hepatorenal syndrome is that the kidneys remain structurally normal, with dysfunction occurring due to intense renal vasoconstriction in response to systemic and splanchnic vasodilation. The condition may improve if liver function recovers.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hepatorenal syndrome is a functional kidney injury that occurs without structural damage to the kidneys","Portal hypertension leads to splanchnic vasodilation and reduced effective circulating volume","Renal vasoconstriction in hepatorenal syndrome is a compensatory response to systemic vasodilation","The condition is potentially reversible if liver function improves"],"references":["Jung CY, Chang JW. Hepatorenal syndrome: Current concepts and future perspectives. Clin Mol Hepatol. 2023 Oct;29(4):891-908. doi: 10.3350/cmh.2023.0024. Epub 2023 Apr 13. PMID: 37050843; PMCID: PMC10577351.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53023"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15049"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53023","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53023"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-05T19:17:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-05T19:20:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7737"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67571"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":